    <%# SEO Article Content %>
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Sleep Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Our free sleep calculator helps you find the optimal times to go to bed or set your alarm by working with your body's natural 90-minute sleep cycles. The page provides two calculation modes. In the first mode, enter the time you need to wake up, and the calculator suggests several ideal bedtimes that align with complete sleep cycles. In the second mode, enter the time you plan to go to bed, and it suggests wake times that coincide with the end of a full cycle. The calculator adds 15 minutes to account for the average time it takes to fall asleep. Results update instantly as you change the time input.
      </p>
      <p>
        Waking at the end of a complete sleep cycle — during a light sleep phase — is the key to feeling alert and refreshed in the morning. When your alarm interrupts deep sleep in the middle of a cycle, you experience sleep inertia: that heavy, groggy feeling that can persist for 30 minutes or more. By timing your sleep in multiples of 90 minutes, you dramatically reduce the chance of waking during deep sleep.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Understanding Sleep Cycles</h2>
      <p>
        Each sleep cycle lasts approximately 90 minutes and progresses through four distinct stages. <strong>Stage 1 (NREM)</strong> is the lightest phase, lasting 1-5 minutes as you transition from wakefulness to sleep. <strong>Stage 2 (NREM)</strong> is slightly deeper, lasting 10-60 minutes, during which your heart rate slows and body temperature drops. <strong>Stage 3 (NREM)</strong> is deep sleep, lasting 20-40 minutes, when tissue repair, immune function, and growth hormone release occur. <strong>REM sleep</strong> follows, lasting 10-60 minutes, during which vivid dreaming occurs and the brain consolidates memories. You cycle through these stages 4-6 times per night, with earlier cycles containing more deep sleep and later cycles containing more REM sleep.
      </p>

      <h3>How Much Sleep Do You Need?</h3>
      <p>
        The National Sleep Foundation recommends 7-9 hours for adults aged 18-64 and 7-8 hours for adults 65 and older. This corresponds to roughly 5-6 complete 90-minute cycles. Teenagers need 8-10 hours, while school-age children need 9-11 hours. Individual needs vary based on genetics, activity level, and overall health. The best indicator is how you feel during the day — if you consistently feel alert and energetic without relying on caffeine, you are likely getting enough sleep.
      </p>

      <h3>Tips for Better Sleep Quality</h3>
      <p>
        Beyond timing your cycles correctly, sleep quality depends on several habits collectively known as sleep hygiene. Maintain a consistent sleep schedule, even on weekends, to regulate your circadian rhythm. Keep your bedroom cool (around 18-20 degrees Celsius), dark, and quiet. Avoid screens for at least 30 minutes before bed, as blue light suppresses melatonin production. Limit caffeine after mid-afternoon and avoid heavy meals within 2-3 hours of bedtime. Regular exercise improves sleep quality, but intense workouts close to bedtime can make it harder to fall asleep.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How does the sleep cycle calculator work?</h3>
      <p>
        The sleep calculator uses 90-minute sleep cycles to determine optimal bedtimes and wake times. Each complete sleep cycle includes light sleep, deep sleep, and REM stages. Waking at the end of a full cycle (rather than in the middle of deep sleep) helps you feel more alert and refreshed. The calculator also adds 15 minutes to account for the average time it takes to fall asleep.
      </p>

      <h3>How many hours of sleep do adults need?</h3>
      <p>
        Most adults need 7 to 9 hours of sleep per night, which corresponds to 5 to 6 complete 90-minute sleep cycles. Individual needs vary — some people function well on 7 hours while others need a full 9. Consistently sleeping fewer than 6 hours is associated with impaired cognitive function, weakened immunity, and increased health risks.
      </p>

      <h3>What is a sleep cycle and how long does it last?</h3>
      <p>
        A sleep cycle lasts approximately 90 minutes and consists of four stages: NREM Stage 1 (light sleep, 1-5 minutes), NREM Stage 2 (slightly deeper, 10-60 minutes), NREM Stage 3 (deep sleep, 20-40 minutes), and REM sleep (dreaming, 10-60 minutes). You typically go through 4-6 cycles per night, with REM periods getting longer toward morning.
      </p>

      <h3>Why do I feel groggy when my alarm goes off?</h3>
      <p>
        Grogginess upon waking, called sleep inertia, is usually caused by your alarm interrupting deep sleep (NREM Stage 3). Deep sleep is the hardest stage to wake from, and doing so leaves you feeling disoriented and tired. By timing your alarm to coincide with the end of a complete sleep cycle (during light sleep), you can minimize sleep inertia and wake feeling more alert.
      </p>

      <h3>Is it better to sleep early or get more sleep cycles?</h3>
      <p>
        Both timing and duration matter. Earlier sleep tends to include more deep sleep in the first half of the night, which is critical for physical recovery. Later sleep cycles have more REM sleep, which supports memory and learning. Ideally, aim for 5-6 complete cycles starting at a consistent time each night. A regular sleep schedule is more beneficial than varying bedtimes even if total hours are the same.
      </p>
    

